heading.text: bdd [package] Electrical system (C510) [Cessna 510 Electrical system BDD]

properties.documentation: This pattern provides a starting point for defining the structural relationships between blocks.
Flight crew must provide the set battery to use action when the battery is not connected but available while other power source are not
Flight crew must not provide the set battery to use action when the battery is disconnected and overheated
Flight crew must not provide the set battery to use action too late when the battery is not connected but available while other power source are not, and the battery is not overheated
Flight crew must provide the set battery to not use action when the battery is connected and it overheats
Flight crew must not provide the set battery to not use action when the battery is connected, charged while other power source are not
Flight crew must not provide the set battery to not use action too late when the battery is connected and it overheats
Safety-critical systems must be powered in emergency and other non-standard situations
Air conditioning and pressuratization must remain operative during the entire flight
Electrical system must never overheat/overload
If the electrical system overheat/overloads, it must be detected and measures taken to prevent further damage
Engine starter must stay operative when engine flames out in-flight
Audio warnings, TCAS, TAWS etc. must stay operative when in emergency situation
Emergency Locator Transmitter (ELT) positioning must always remain operative after an accident
Pitot-static heat must remain operative when icing forms on pitot tubes
Aircraft systems monitor (engines, landing gear, pressure, tempertature) must remain operative when a monitored system malfunctions or fails
Essential aircraft systems must be powered during the entire flight
Avionics (CNS systems, both primary/standby) must remain operative during the entire flight
Flaps must remain operative during the entire flight
The electrical system must collect and verify feedback about the current battery charge.
The electrical system must detect and alert to a faulty feedback.
The electrical system must detect and alert to a critical user system that needs a power, including if the power is needed immediately, and account for potential delays in the power setup/delivery.
The electrical system shall predict, whether alternate power sources may become online quickly enough.
The electrical system must collect and provide feedbacks quickly enough.
